    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="963"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d963">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/425: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-19">August 19,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>988. Your 1458, August 9, indicates that Soviet Government intends to observe on
                    the basis of reciprocity the Geneva Red Cross Convention of July 27, 1929. The
                    Department would appreciate being informed whether the Soviet Union also intends
                    to observe the prisoner of war convention signed at Geneva on the same date<note
                        n="48" xml:id="d963fn48">For text, see <ref target="frus1929v01#pg_336">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1929, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 336</ref>; or League of Nations Treaty
                        Series, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">cxviii</hi>, p. 343.</note> or the
                    convention on that subject signed on July 6, 1906.<note n="49" xml:id="d963fn49"
                        >International Red Cross Convention, for the Amelioration of the Condition
                        of the Wounded of the Armies in the Field, signed at Geneva; for text, see
                            <ref target="frus1906p2#pg_1559">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1906, pt. 2, p. 1559</ref>; or
                        35 Stat. 1885.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
